purpose:
The MTC registry is an FDA post-marketing requirement for Sponsors with an approved long-acting GLP-1 RA. Because of the rarity of MTC and in order to minimize inconvenience to patients, physicians, and state cancer registries, FDA encouraged sponsors of long-acting GLP-1 receptor agonists to work collaboratively to conduct this registry. Consequently, the MTC Registry Consortium has been formed for this purpose. The MTC Registry Consortium refers to the Sponsors with approved long-acting GLP-1 receptor agonists who have a contractual agreement to participate in the MTC Registry. Novo Nordisk Inc., AstraZeneca (formerly Bristol-Myers Squibb's Diabetes Division), and GlaxoSmithKline currently serve as the Sponsors for this program.  Additional Sponsors, who receive FDA approval for their compounds, are expected to join the MTC Consortium. It is anticipated the MTC registry will continue for 15 years after FDA approval of each respective compound (or for the duration agreed upon between each respective Sponsor and FDA).

The objectives of this prospective active surveillance program are:
1. To systematically monitor the annual incidence of MTC in the U.S. through NAACCR to identify any possible increase related to the introduction of long-acting GLP-1 receptor agonists into the U.S. market
2. To establish a registry of incident cases of MTC in adults in the U.S. in order to characterize their medical histories and possible risk factors, including history of treatment with long-acting GLP-1 receptor agonists
description: Utah Cancer Registry will identify newly diagnosed (in past 6-12 months) MTC cases from their DMS system. Utah Cancer Registry will mail the MTC Registry patient letter and permission form to each identified new MTC case.  The form will serve as the patient's consent to release the requested UCR data to the researcher, United BioSource Corporation (UBC). If the patient is interested, he or she will return the signed permission form to UCR. If UCR does not receive a response from the patient, UCR will contact the patient via telephone making 3 calls followed by a second letter. At least 2 of the calls will be made on the weekend and at least 2 calls made in the evening. UCR will post to secure UBC secure FTP (file transfer protocol) study portal a file containing the first name, last name, mailing address and telephone number for the new diagnosed MTC patients.

purpose:
The purpose of the Utah Cancer Survivors Needs Assessment is to determine the gaps in cancer care. The Utah Department of Health's Cancer Control Program (UCCP) will use the information to inform UCCP's future program planning as well as share the needs assessment's findings with its partners.  

After treatment, cancer survivors' care needs vary and can include health, psycho-social, physical, financial, personal, system of care, community resources, and education/information needs.  A statewide needs assessment has not been conducted to identify cancer survivor's needs after treatment and any perceived gaps in existing care.  The proposed assessment will address this lack of information.

Utah's cancer survivors input regarding the gaps in survivor services will inform UCCP's future program planning so the programs can more effectively fill survivors' needs.  Sharing the findings with UCCP's local and national partners will increase the assessment's impact. 

Given the purpose outlined above, the objectives of the study are to: (1) identify the needs of Utah cancer survivors after treatment is completed; (2) analyze whether statewide rural/urban and/or socioeconomic disparities in needs exist; (3) identify if needs vary by cancer type; and (4) disseminate the findings. 

This study will focus on cancer care after active treatment through end of life.
description:
To achieve UCCP's objectives, the University of Utah's Center for Public Policy & Administration (CPPA) would like to conduct a systematic, population-based survey to identify cancer survivors' met and unmet needs.  We would like to meet with the Utah Cancer Registry (UCR) to discuss UCR's potential role on this project and CPPA's dual goals of obtaining cancer survivors input while assuring survivor's confidentiality.  

Since UCR maintains the most complete of registry of cancer survivor's in the state, we hope that the UCR will work with us to reach out to survivors and solicit their participation in a telephone survey.  A phone survey completed by trained, professional telephone interviewers would result in the most complete responses from respondents who agree to participate in the survey.  Another survey method could be used if UCR feels it is advisable.

UCR's role on the study would be to:
•	Advise the needs assessment team on survey methodology and review the final survey tool.
•	Select a sample of cancer survivors to be surveyed.
•	Contact the individuals in the sample to determine their willingness to participate in the survey before the individual is contacted by the needs assessment team.

In addition, the needs assessment team would like to anonymously link survey results to basic demographic data retained in the registry.  This data could include items such as gender, age at diagnosis, race and ethnicity, socio-economic indicators, and county of residence.  Specific data fields can be determined if the project is approved.
projecttitle: Utah's Cancer Survivors Needs Assessment

purpose:
This is a study that will be done in collaboration with the UDOH (with Brad Belnap and Jessie Mandle, part of the cancer control division).

The purpose is to implement a broad set of evidence-based survivorship strategies in a subset of grantees, that will have the short-term results of increasing knowledge of cancer survivor needs, increasing survivor knowledge of treatment and follow-up care, and increasing provider knowledge of cancer treatment-related guidelines. Intermediate outcomes include development of best practices in survivorship among grantees and identification of capacity needed to sustain a broad program of survivorship interventions. The long term outcome is the widespread adoption of practice- and evidence-based, sustainable, survivorship activites leading to increased duration of life for cancer survivors. 

Objectives:
-Implement specific surveillance strategies to drive cancer survivorship initiatives
-Develop and implement specific strategies that facilitate community/clinical linkages to access community resources to support survivorship intiative
-Accelerate the spread and reach of evidence-based and promising survivorship practices by dissemination of results and lessons learned.
description: Partner with local cancer registry staff and other relevant local partners to use local cancer registry data to populate survivor care plans for cancer survivors. Staff will work with their local cancer registry staff to utilize existing surveillance data on diagnosis and treatment for those diagnosed with cancer. This data will be used to populate cancer survivorship care plans that will be distributed to the survivor population. It is anticipated that at a minimum survivors with the five most commonly diagnosed and leading causes of cancer death will receive survivorship care plans.
projecttitle: Increasing the Implementation of Evidence-Based Cancer Survivorship Interventions to Increase Quality and Duration of Life among Cancer Patients

purpose:
The proposed study will convene up to 5 focus groups - each consisting of 8-10 participants - to understand the cost and benefit trade-off that adolescent and young adult (AYA) cancer survivors face in utilizing regular follow-up cancer care. AYA survivors often suffer from long-term health conditions called late effects (e.g., cardiovascular disease, cognitive impairment, fertility issues and organ system damage) and managing these late effects requires regular follow-up care. The focus groups will be conducted to inform the development of a novel survey based on the Contingent Valuation (CV) method that will aid in assessing the divergence between cost and benefits of follow-up cancer care to AYA survivors. CV surveys will ask AYA survivors carefully designed questions to estimate their willingness to pay - that is, the maximum amount of money survivors will pay for annual follow-up visits aimed at reducing the risk of late effects. Monetary values that survivors place on follow-up care visits are a measure of their perceived benefits (e.g., improved quality of life, better educational outcomes, lower health care expenses) resulting from the potential health risk reduction. Focus groups will be implemented to evaluate AYA survivors' willingness to pay for follow-up care at Huntsman Cancer Institute's Late Effects Clinic, which provides care for survivors of pediatric, adolescent and young adult cancers. These focus groups will ask participants questions:

a)     To ascertain their willingness to pay for risk-based annual follow-up cancer care to manage, prevent or reduce the risk of late effects. This will provide information on the distribution (i.e., minimum, mean, median, maximum) of survivors' willingness to pay.

b)     To elicit survivors' preferences regarding the mode of payment (i.e., do participants prefer paying an out-of-pocket payment, additional insurance premium or supplemental health monitoring policy for annual follow-up visits?) and frequency of payment (i.e., do participants prefer making payment monthly, semi-annually or annually?).

c)     To assess survivors' knowledge and experiences with late effects of cancer, ease of communication with physicians, satisfaction with insurance, and attitude toward regular follow-up health care.

Responses to these questions will help in evaluating whether survivors' preferences regarding mode/frequency of payment and other characteristics affect willingness to pay. To inform our cost and benefit analysis, we will be comparing participants' willingness to pay for follow-up care to actual costs of care at the Late Effects Clinic.
description:

purpose:
Within 10 years after diagnosis, 40% of pediatric cancer patients have one or more late complications. Yet, as more patients survive their devastating diseases, the long term implications for their future quality of life, health and economic consequences are undefined.

Purpose: To define, manage and improve long-term health and health care outcomes for pediatric cancer patients throughout their life course.

Main Objective: Define the health care costs associated with the development of late effects in pediatric cancer patients treated at Primary Children's Hospital (PCH), Intermountain Healthcare (IH), University of Utah Health Care (UUHSC) and other hospitals and clinics in the Utah Department of Health (UDOH) and develop infrastructure to track and manage these patients through their life course.

Impact:  This is the first comprehensive assessment of the long-term health and costs of childhood cancer survivors to define, manage and improve long-term health and health care outcomes for pediatric cancer patients throughout their life course.

Specific Aims:

Aim 1: Establish a database of all pediatric oncology patients treated at PCH from January 1, 1986-December 31, 2012

Aim 2: Define the subset of patients who develop late effects or chronic conditions beginning 1 year after completion of initial therapy. In addition, as a comparison, we will generate descriptive information on the health care costs for patients who have not developed late effects, as well as on a comparison sample (sibling sample and/or population based sample) without a history of cancer.

           Hypothesis: Patients surviving certain cancers, such as central nervous system tumors, will be most likely to develop late effects beginning 1 year after completion of initial therapy. Survivors will have higher health care costs than siblings and the general population.

Aim 3: Determine costs associated with late effect conditions for these patients and continuing over time.

           Hypothesis: Survivors of certain cancers that require higher dose radiation or chemotherapy, or with multiple chronic conditions will have the highest health care costs. Additionally, survivors who live in rural locations (e.g., lack close access to oncology providers) or who live in locations far from PCH will be at a higher risk for developing late effects that result in high health care costs.

Aim 4: Compare chronic condition outcomes and cost among children managed according to evidence-based late effects guidelines developed by the Children's Oncology Group and those managed without a process model.

           Hypothesis: Survivors who are managed according to late effects guidelines will have lower health care costs due to better management of late effect conditions than survivors managed without a process model.

Aim 5: Develop innovative decision support tools to facilitate treatment and survivor care plans.
description: We are looking to obtain treatment, ethnicity (via last name classifier), and other diagnosis information for a cohort of pediatric cancer patients we have identified through the Intermountain Cancer Registry.
projecttitle: Primary Children's Pediatric Cancer: Life Course Health Care Complications and Costs

purpose:
Adolescent and young adult (AYA) cancer survivors are a growing population who face unique health and psychosocial issues. These include late health effects of treatment as well as challenges in receiving appropriate health care after completion of cancer therapy. Obtaining accurate data about actual receipt of cancer therapy is a recognized challenge both for long-term patient management and for research on cancer outcomes. Cancer registries obtain data from hospitals and other facilities to document first course of cancer therapy, but because an individual patient may receive care in multiple settings including hospitals, clinics, and radiation centers, treatment data obtained by registries are often incomplete. All-payer claims databases (APCD) may be a useful resource for obtaining documentation of cancer care as well as health outcomes for AYA cancer survivors. Utah is one of the first states to establish a viable APCD. However, the usefulness of APCD to study cancer survivors has not been assessed.
Aim 1: Evaluate the utility of APCD claims to identify AYA cancer diagnoses and treatment
Aim 2: Determine the ability to link APCD records to individual cancer patient identifiers in the UCR to populate cancer treatment summaries.
description:
Analysis of unidentified APCD claims data.
Participate in application to UDOH for identified APCD data.
Merge APCD to UCR records, evaluate linkage, and analyze to assess ability to obtain cancer treatment data from the claims.
Dr. Sweeney is a co-investigator on the project.
projecttitle: Improving cancer treatment summaries for adolescent and young adults using all payer claims database

purpose:
It is with pleasure that, on behalf of the International Association of Cancer Registries (IACR) and the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC), I invite your registry to submit a dataset for volume XI of Cancer Incidence in Five Continents (CI5). This longstanding collaboration between IARC and IACR serves as a unique source of cancer incidence data from high-quality population-based cancer registries around the world. It continues to be an invaluable resource for cancer research and cancer control worldwide, and is the primary source of GLOBOCAN and national estimates in 184 countries by cancer, sex and age, presently for the year 2012 (http://globocan.iarc.fr).

As with previous volumes of CI5, to be eligible to submit data, registries should be population-based, voting or associate members of IACR, and collect information on patients diagnosed with all cancer sites and types (except non-melanoma skin cancer) and in all age groups.
description: Previously, UCR's data has been submitted by SEER, once SEER has the approval from UCR. UCR needs to review the call for data and send approvals along to SEER.
projecttitle: Cancer Incidence in 5 Contients XI

purpose: Within the UPDB linked data with the Utah Cancer Registry, we propose to construct a population-based endometrial cancer patient cohort covering the state of Utah. Our specific aims are: (1) To assemble a population-based cohort of 3,400 endometrial cancer patients and 17,000 age-matched cancer-free women for a comparison group, to investigate the incidence of long-term health effects due to endometrial cancer treatment, (2) To assess the feasibility of administering questionnaires to assess lifestyle factors in a sample of the endometrial cancer survivors (n=500) and cancer-free women for a comparison group (n=500), (3) To determine the feasibility of collecting detailed cancer treatment information such as chemotherapy agents from medical records by conducting medical record abstraction among a sample of endometrial cancer patients (n=200), (4) To compare the quality of information obtained from the existing records and the self-report from the questionnaire on late effects, comorbidities, and cancer treatment (n=1,000).
description: To assess the feasibility of administering questionnaires to assess lifestyle factors in a sample of the endometrial cancer survivors (n=500) and cancer-free women for a comparison group (n=500)
